Let me think about this problem from a truly different perspective. What if the bug was introduced or relates to a change between Helidon 4.1.x and 4.3.x? Let me search for any recent changes to the dbclient module:

Actually, the repo has only one commit. Let me not worry about that.

OK, I want to look at the code one more time, focusing specifically on the `MongoDbStatement` base class and how `prepareStatement` works:

```java
String prepareStatement(DbClientServiceContext serviceContext) {
    String statement = serviceContext.statement();
    DbStatementParameters stmtParams = serviceContext.statementParameters();
    if (stmtParams instanceof DbIndexedStatementParameters indexed) {
        List<Object> params = indexed.parameters();
        return StatementParsers.indexedParser(statement, params).convert();
    } else if (stmtParams instanceof DbNamedStatementParameters named) {
        Map<String, Object> params = named.parameters();
        return StatementParsers.namedParser(statement, params).convert();
    }
    return statement;
}
```

This reads params from the service context. The service context gets its params from `DbStatementBase.doExecute`:

```java
DbClientServiceContext serviceContext =
        new DbClientServiceContextImpl(context, statementType(), stmtFuture, queryFuture, parameters);
```

Where `parameters` is set by `namedParam`/`indexedParam` via the mapper.

Wait, I just noticed something! In `DbStatementBase`:

```java
private DbStatementParameters parameters;
```

And `doExecute`:
```java
protected <T> T doExecute(BiFunction<CompletableFuture<Long>, DbClientServiceContext, T> function) {
    ...
    DbClientServiceContext serviceContext =
            new DbClientServiceContextImpl(context, statementType(), stmtFuture, queryFuture, parameters);
    ...
}
```

It uses `parameters` directly (not `parameters()` which handles null -> UNDEFINED). If `parameters` is null, then `DbClientServiceContextImpl.statementParameters()` would return null. Then in `JdbcStatement.prepareStatement(DbClientServiceContext)`, null would not match `instanceof DbIndexedStatementParameters` or `instanceof DbNamedStatementParameters`, falling through to `prepareStatement(stmtName, stmt)`.

But this only happens if `namedParam`/`indexedParam` or `addParam` was never called. If the user calls `namedParam`, then `parameters` would be set to a `DbNamedStatementParameters`.

Wait... let me look at `namedParam` one more time:

```java
@Override
public S namedParam(Object parameters) {
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    Class<Object> theClass = (Class<Object>) parameters.getClass();
    params(context.dbMapperManager().toNamedParameters(parameters, theClass));
    return identity();
}
```

And `params(Map<String, ?> parameters)`:

```java
@Override
public S params(Map<String, ?> parameters) {
    parameters.forEach(this::addParam);
    return identity();
}
```

And `addParam(String name, Object parameter)`:

```java
@Override
public S addParam(String name, Object parameter) {
    if (parameters == null) {
        parameters = new DbNamedStatementParameters();
    }
    parameters.addParam(name, parameter);
    return identity();
}
```

OK, so after `namedParam`, `this.parameters` is set to `new DbNamedStatementParameters()`. This is passed to `doExecute` and then to `DbClientServiceContextImpl`. Then `statementParameters()` returns this instance. Then `JdbcStatement.prepareStatement(DbClientServiceContext)` checks `instanceof DbNamedStatementParameters` and processes named params. All correct.

